"1435–Female":"1435–Deceased","1460–1539":"1460–1539","1398–1447":"1398–1447","1403–Female":"1403–Deceased","1403":"1403","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","1460":"1460","about 1430":"about 1430","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","Barrow in Furness, Lancashire, England":"Barrow in Furness, Lancashire, England","Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dixon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Dickson  , a patronymic from the personal name   Dick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dixion","meanings":["Altered form of English   Dixon  ."]},{"name":"Dickson","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Dick   + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":119,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Dixon was born about 1430, in Hawkshead, Lancashire, England, his father, John Dixon, was 33 and his mother, Mrs. John Dixon, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Lady Nicholas Dixon."},"et":{"about 1430–":"umbes 1430–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1460–1539":"1460–1539","1398–1447":"1398–1447","1403–Female":"1403–Surnud","1403":"1403","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","1460":"1460","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","Barrow in Furness, Lancashire, England":"Barrow in Furness, Lancashire, England","Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1430–":"noin 1430–Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1435–Female":"1435–Kuollut","1460–1539":"1460–1539","1398–1447":"1398–1447","14